DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(76)90022-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393276900222
AB  - Empirical application of distributed lags has been a notable development in testing macro-economic relationships. Use of stock adjustment models has been justified theoretically in some areas; in many others it has been characterized by ad hoc specification. Progress toward analysis of the adjustment of investment has been made in the framework of the theory of the firm. A parallel analysis of cash balances derived from current approaches to the demand for money finds the lag structure of stock adjustment models unsuitable as a representation of the implicit adjustment in these models of money demand.
